
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lslogins` etela'ati ra darbareye user-ha va login-haye system namayesh midahad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad ta user-haye fa'al, akharin zamane vorood, va etela'ate digari ra bebinid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lslogins` --> 📜 Namayesh list-e sadeye user-ha va etela'at asli.
    🔹 `lslogins -u` --> 👤 Namayesh list-e user-ha va UID-haye aanha.
    🔹 `lslogins -b` --> ⏰ Namayesh akharin zamane vorood baraye har user.
    🔹 `lslogins -p` --> 🔒 Namayesh etela'at password (agar dastres dashte bashid).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lslogins

    🔹 Namayesh list-e sadeye user-ha va etela'at asli.

    $ lslogins -u

    🔹 Namayesh list-e user-ha va UID-haye aanha.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lslogins -b

    🔹 Etela'ati ra darbareye akharin zamane vorood baraye har user namayesh midahad, ke be shoma komak mikonad ta fa'aliyathaye user-ha ra peygiri konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lslogins` command displays information about users and logins on the system. It helps you see active users, last login times, and other details.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lslogins` --> 📜 Show a basic list of users and main information.
    🔹 `lslogins -u` --> 👤 Show a list of users and their User IDs (UIDs).
    🔹 `lslogins -b` --> ⏰ Show the last login time for each user.
    🔹 `lslogins -p` --> 🔒 Show password information (if you have access).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lslogins

    🔹 Show a basic list of users and main information.

    $ lslogins -u

    🔹 Show a list of users and their User IDs (UIDs).

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lslogins -b

    🔹 Displays information about the last login time for each user, which helps you track user activity.
